<div class="comment comment-even" id="comment-100053568">
	<div class="comment-content" id="comment-100053568-content">
		<span id="comment-100053568-content"><p>I&#39;m not sure how Brian&#39;s idea of combining these three Ruby-CLR-bridge efforts would be a &quot;solution&quot; to JOHN problem or that of Open Source developers in general.  It might help get this project &quot;done&quot; sooner or without burning out.  It is true, that when you &quot;spread&quot; the pain around maybe it doesn&#39;t hurt so much.  But significant projects really REQUIRE the devotion of key individuals or else nothing gets done or you end up with a hodgepodge of democratic constructed &quot;Politically Correct&quot; group-think software.  That means somebody ends up &quot;giving it away, like a teenager full of raging hormones&quot;.  But unless the person doing this is supported financially this behavior is not sustainable and leads to burn out and the demise of otherwise great projects.</p>

<p>Brian&#39;s idea reminds me of something my girlfriend often says: &quot;Americans tend to jump for solutions (often the first one that pops into their head) before trying to really understand the problem... good solutions (IF they are actually even necessary) tend to become visible only AFTER you truly understand the problem&quot;.  </p>

<p>One reason she &quot;picks on&quot; Americans is because I am one (she&#39;s Italian and here I am living in Pisa which makes me kind of conspicuous) and the other reason is that she is RIGHT about us, as a general rule (I&#39;ll admit that our &quot;from the hip, cowboy behavior&quot; can also be a VIRTUE if properly balanced... but at the same time it CAN and OFTEN DOES get us into a mess).  Brian might not be an American but his statement reminded me of one (this is NOT a bash at Brian, just a statement of fact).</p>

<p>John&#39;s problem, and that of many (maybe most?) Open Source developers, seems to be that he needs to feed his family and pay the rent with money left over for retirement.  It is not too much to ask, I think.</p>

<p>But his biggest problem (and virtue) is that he seems to be ETHICAL and unwilling to subversively cheat on his day job.  He seems to feel guilty for not contributing more toward the success of his paying business venture.  Maybe I&#39;m wrong, but it is my impression that is how most open source projects are funded, on the backs of employers who don&#39;t know they are supporting it (or who turn the other cheek, like a wife to a mistress, and tolerate it in order to get a precious slice of some talented person&#39;s time).  I prefer John&#39;s approach, frankly.  It is honest, fair, and correct.  And I wish more people were like that!</p>

<p>Maybe John (and most Open Source developers?) is somewhat like a struggling actor passionately wanting to &quot;make art&quot;, and waiting tables to pay the rent, while also hoping he might someday be compensated for the &quot;dues&quot; he has paid.  But the big driving force is the urge to succeed at acting and do something significant.  Hope that&#39;s not too bad a metaphor, John.</p>

<p>John might need a &quot;Patron&quot; who basically says to him &quot;go forth and make art&quot; and supports him financially so he can explore his talents and do what he loves.  Yet I don&#39;t know if that is what he wants, because I don&#39;t know what motivates him.  Maybe he wants a &quot;really big house and corporate jet&quot;.  In which case he either needs a really big patron or should focus on the paying gigs.</p>

<p>I&#39;m no expert on this, but I believe most of the great artwork of the renaissance happened under such patron supported conditions.  I think it was the norm.  And I think it is called for now.</p>

<p>In reading John&#39;s blog, I got the feeling he might have been &quot;pinging&quot; for just such a patron.  And frankly I hope he finds one.  Are any &quot;potential patrons&quot; listening out there?  If so, toss some coins (or bank notes) into this man&#39;s hat :-)</p>

<p>Less selfishly, John also seems to be &quot;championing the cause&quot; for some form of &quot;meaningful&quot; support to deserving people doing open source work.</p>

<p>I think the most pressing priority is finding a patron FOR JOHN.  If that can happen, the championing can continue without burning out and other&#39;s can benefit.  So being brutally selfish first but not forgetting the roots makes a lot of sense, I think.  While you are up in Microsoft land, be *aggressive*.  Ask for the direct financial support for YOURSELF rather than bashfully pushing for generic assistance to open source community (not suggesting you are bashful, John, just saying to be extra assertive while you might be speaking into the right ears).  This is the time to be a salesman, I think.</p>

<p>Best regards and good luck,<br />
Pat</p></span>
