<div class="comment comment-odd" id="comment-100053574">
	<div class="comment-content" id="comment-100053574-content">
		<span id="comment-100053574-content"><p>Hi &quot;null&quot;,</p>

<p>It was mighty brave of you say your name in public.</p>

<p>You asked:<br />
&gt; Doesn&#39;t expecting to be paid for <br />
&gt; OSS work also belong in the &quot;sense <br />
&gt; of entitlement&quot; box?</p>

<p>How about cooling it with the clich??s, they are kind of &quot;null&quot;.</p>

<p>OSS means &quot;Open Source Software&quot;... NOT working for free just because you think you are some kind of hero.  It means that the source code is free to anyone.  NOT that it is somehow taboo to be paid for developing it.</p>

<p>The problem really isn&#39;t about people doing OSS work in their &quot;spare time&quot;.  That is fine.  The problem is when someone invests so much of their time in doing worthy OSS work (stuff that is not just fun little project FOR THEM SELF) that it often turns out to not be spare time any more... it becomes their life.  Why should such persons starve???  Why should they be punished for contributing to the world?  Maybe you think it is better to just NOT have this great work get done???</p>

<p>Why do you have it in with someone for wanting to be paid for doing something worthy.  And what is more, isn&#39;t the &quot;patron&quot; who is willing (knowingly) to pay for such work (that they don&#39;t own rights to) a noble thing?  Even if they do make a profit in other ways?</p>

<p>The reality is, and you know it, many OSS developers (but certainly NOT all) *steal* from their employers to support their &quot;climbing&quot; on the OSS software mountain.  Come out of your denial and get real.  OSS isn&#39;t all about being a hero... there are a lot of people doing it for &quot;free&quot; while actually being paid by their employer (unknowingly for that mission) because they are bored in their day jobs.  Even if they don&#39;t &quot;code on the job&quot; they do often &quot;think about their beloved OSS work&quot; while supposedly &quot;working&quot;.  And if they do that without the knowledge and consent of their employers they are unethical and dishonest... not exactly heroes.</p>

<p>Your attitude seems to me like you want to shoot good people in the foot just because YOU think this is a bad thing.  If you don&#39;t like people doing this... then YOU don&#39;t do it.</p>

<p>Maybe you are just envious and *wish* you were &quot;good enough&quot; to be paid for doing OSS work.  John certainly is from the perspective of both a software developer and a contributor to society at large in terms of public awareness of important issues (so say nothing of his beautiful pictures).  How much of your freely given development time has turned into something useful for other people?  Where is YOUR development blog full of GREAT and USEFUL information?  How many of your thoughts (along with your blunders) have you documented in the light of day for everybody to see and use, for &quot;free&quot;.  Where are your &quot;say it like it is without political correctness&quot; commentaries on software, political, and life issues?  Nowhere, I would guess, given that you don&#39;t even have the courage to post your name.    </p>

<p>Thanks for listening, &quot;null&quot;</p>

<p>Pat</p></span>
