		<span id="comment-100053576-content"><p>Well... hmm...</p>

<p>Rails does a couple things I think are interesting. First they make it easy to collaborate by using Trac. Now don&#39;t get me wrong, Trac is not my fave piece of software, but as far as collaboration efforts and bug reports go, it&#39;s pretty effective. On the .NET side Jira seems mildly popular, but it&#39;s a lot more confusing IMO.</p>

<p>So that&#39;s one. And easy way to be heard.</p>

<p>Another is the TextDrive relationship. I signed up with TextDrive for two reasons: They supported Rails on their systems, and half my money (or something like that) goes back into the Rails project itself.</p>

<p>I was/am happy to give that financial support. In fact, I&#39;m still paying even though I haven&#39;t touched that account for months (I moved to VPSLand) and the QoS was about the worst I&#39;ve experienced from a hosting provider.</p>

<p>Now I need to get around to cancelling that, but I think the idea of &quot;Value Added&quot; deals like that has merit. It worked for me anyways. I&#39;m sure there&#39;s got to be a .NET/Ruby business out there that would happily make a deal to accept donations for the RubyClr. Would it be enough to keep you busy full-time? I&#39;d be surprised... but what do I know?</p></span>
