<div class="comment comment-odd" id="comment-100053578">
	<div class="comment-content" id="comment-100053578-content">
		<span id="comment-100053578-content"><p>John, you pose one of the most interesting problems facing open source software.  </p>

<p>Your idea of finding companies that have a vested interest in developing a free / open piece of software works in more scenarios.  Take bar code scanning for instance.  There are a LOT of companies that would benefit from contributing to an open bar code scanning libray.  These are not necessarily very big companies either, they could be your average ISV that builds an inventory tracking application for a particular vertical market.</p>

<p>The trick is to entice a company enough to allow a developer to work on this project part or even full time.  The other model is for them to donate financially.  A bounty system seems to be one way to pay for developers to work professionally on these types of projects.</p>

<p>Sourceforge already has a &quot;donate&quot; button but more must be done to educate CTOs and CEOs that developing open libraries to get &quot;x&quot; done will save them from having to deal with crappy 3rd party proprietary SDKs royalties and poor support.</p>

<p>Just take the Java world as an example, there are hundreds of great open source solutions to the very problems your company needs to solve in it&#39;s own enterprise and commercial applications.  Without this eco system Java would not be where it is today.</p>

<p>The old ways of charging for components and SDKs that do things the community can build, support, and fix itself are going away.  I don&#39;t know of a developer that wouldn&#39;t rather use open source when a solution is available.</p></span>
	</div>
